In plugin/core/gvloadimage_core.c there is the following:

```c
...
ifdef HAVE_SYS_MMAN_H
    us->data = mmap(0, statbuf.st_size, PROT_READ, MAP_SHARED, fd, 0);
#else
    us->data = malloc(statbuf.st_size);
    read(fd, us->data, statbuf.st_size);
#endif
    us->must_inline = TRUE;
                break;
            default:
                break;
        }
        if (us->data)
            us->datafree = ps_freeimage;
...
```

If `mmap` is available (when `HAVE_SYS_MMAN_H` is defined) it is used instead of `malloc`. However the surrounding code seems to expect `us->data` to end up as `NULL` if the allocation failed. `mmap` doesn't return `NULL`, but `MAP_FAILED` on allocation failure. The result is that this code will not notice an `mmap` failure and attempt to use the invalid pointer `-1`.

The same code also appears in plugin/core/gvloadimage_lasi.c (copy paste?).

I think the cleanest fix is to check `us->data` against `MAP_FAILED` in the `HAVE_SYS_MMAN_H` case and set it to `NULL` if true. Having said that, the other case has the problem that it uses `us->data` before checking `malloc` succeeded as well.

