There is a lot of repetition in styling nodes and edges in dot (and probably the other GraphViz languages(?) too). One could group nodes and edges and defined a style for them all, however, that only works when one is not trying to make a complex graph and has only a few nodes. I found the request from @GadgetSteve to create classes for nodes and edges, and I thought that I would bring it up again since nothing has come from it in three years. So here is his suggestion again, and I like it.
```
digraph new_feature_request {
  node [ shape = circle, color = black ];
  node.foo [ shape = rectangle, color = red ];
  node.bar [ shape = diamond, color = green ];
  node.foo.bar [ shape = ellipse ];

  edge [ style = solid, arrowsize = 1 ];
  edge.foo [ style = dashed ];
  edge.bar [ style = dotted ];
  edge.baz [ arrowsize = 2 ];

  C -> R [ label = "solid big black arrow", class = baz ];
  R -> D [ label = "dotted big black arrow", class = "baz foo" ];
  D -> E [ label = "bold big black arrow", class = "foo baz", style = bold ];

  graph.foo [ /* etc. */ ];
}
```

However, that is not the end of problems with styling. I was recently experimenting with HTML tables. That is when I found that the `style` attribute in the table was still the GraphViz `style` attribute. That makes it very hard to make tables and other HTML labels a pain to style. Currently, the HTML labels use very deprecated HTML attributes. They are so old that I have forgotten how to use them after learning the CSS to achieve the same effects. So I propose that once an HTML label is invoked, the `style` attribute be given to CSS styles.

```
graph foo {
  bar [
    shape="plaintext",
    label=< /* this triggers style going over to css */
      <table style="border-collapse: collapse; border: none;">
        <tr>
          <td style="background-color:#ffcccc;" post="LightRed">Light red</td>
          <td style="font-style:italic;" port="Italic">Italic text</td>
          <td style="border: 4px solid #00ff00;" port="SolidBlack">Solid black border</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    > /* the style attribute goes back to GraphViz styles. */
  ];
}
```

GraphViz could go one step further and have CSS styles predefined too. Using the above suggestion by Steve Barnes and my example table, here is how it could look.

```
digraph new_feature_request {
  styles [
    gvss = {
      node         [ shape = circle,    color = black ];
      node.foo     [ shape = rectangle, color = red ];
      node.bar     [ shape = diamond,   color = green ];
      node.foo.bar [ shape = ellipse ];

      edge     [ style = solid, arrowsize = 1 ];
      edge.foo [ style = dashed ];
      edge.bar [ style = dotted ];
      edge.baz [ arrowsize = 2 ];
    }
    css = {
      table.bar      { border-collapse: collapse; border: none; };
      td.light_red   { background-color:#ffcccc; }
      td.italic      { font-style:italic; }
      td.solid_black { border: 4px solid #00ff00; }
    }
  ]

  C [ label = "black circle" ];
  R [ label = "red rectangle", class = "foo" ];
  D [ label = "green diamond", class = "bar" ];
  E [ label = "green ellipse", class = "foo bar" ];

  C -> R [ label = "solid big black arrow", class = baz ];
  R -> D [ label = "dotted big black arrow", class = "baz foo" ];
  D -> E [ label = "bold big black arrow", class = "foo baz", style = bold ];

  graph.foo [ /* etc. */ ];

  bar [
    shape="plaintext",
    label=< /* the style and class attributes go over to CSS */
      <table class="bar">
        <tr>
          <td class="light_red" port="LightRed">Light <span style="font-size:10pt">red</span></td>
          <td class="italic" port="Italic">Italic text</td>
          <td class="solid_black" port="SolidBlack">Solid black border</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    > /* ends the HTML and CSS and the style and class attributes go back to GraphViz and GVSS*/
  ];
}
```

And if one is making several graphs using the same styles, `styles` could have an attribute of `file`.

```
  styles [ file="style_file.gvss" ] /* GraphViz style sheet */
