The class `IncVPSC` in lib/vpsc privately inherits from `VPSC`. However the library uses `IncVPSC` objects as if they can be substituted for `VPSC` objects. The main obvious case is `newIncVPSC`:

```cpp
VPSC* newIncVPSC(int n, Variable* vs[], int m, Constraint* cs[]) {
  return (VPSC*)new IncVPSC(n,vs,m,cs);
}
```

Note that a C-style cast is needed to force this operation here because `VPSC` is an inaccessible base of `IncVPSC`. I.e. you're not supposed to convert `IncVPSC` pointers to `VPSC`. This is exposed to users because this function is part of the lib/vpsc API.

This looks like some sort of kludge that was introduced when bridging this functionality to C. I don't immediately see why `IncVPSC` cannot *publicly* inherit from `VPSC`, and this would be my suggested fix.

