While working on the recent string-interning-based stuff like #517, #1984, and #2089, I realized the implementation uses more memory than it needs to. An interned string ends up in a struct like the following:

```c
typedef struct {
    Dtlink_t link;
    uint64_t refcnt: sizeof(uint64_t) * 8 - 1;
    uint64_t is_html: 1;
    char *s;
    char store[1];    /* this is actually a dynamic array */
} refstr_t;
```

As the comment indicates, the last member is not really 1 byte but rather a dynamically sized array.¹ When memory is allocated to intern a string, the string's length is taken into account when allocating memory for the backing `refstr_t`. Then the string is written to the `store` member, and the `s` member is set to point to this. `s` is what gets returned to the caller. Later on, struct-field-offset-based arithmetic is used to reconstruct a `refstr_t` pointer from a string pointer.

The wasteful part in here is `s`. It always points to `store`. So we don't actually need `s`, but can just return the address of `store`. On a 64-bit platform this is wasting 8 bytes per interned string. In many graphs, it's possible that the size of the interned string dictionary occupies more memory than just duplicating and not interning strings at all would have.

¹ This kind of thing might look strange when you first come across it, but it is a common pattern for representing header-prefixed dynamic blobs. You often see network code using something like this to represent packet data or protocol libraries using it for Tag-Length-Value (TLV) data. The modern way to do this is actually to declare the array with no length, `[]`, a so-called Variable Length Array In Struct (VLAIS).

