## Additional info

I guess that when graphviz generates a horizontal layout, it will reverse the height and width in a vertical layout, and then implement a horizontal layout by rotating the coordinates of the elements in the graph.<br/><br/>
However, it is more difficult to deal with the label of the `cluster`, because the label of the `cluster` is placed on the left and right sides of the `cluster` before being `rotated`, which brings a problem. The label of the cluster may stretch the vertical distance between ranks. and margin size.<br/><br/>
Graphviz adopts the principle of greed. The cluster that is calculated first will give priority to the vertical distance between ranks or the size of the margin. Different execution orders may make the margin sometimes take effect and sometimes not take effect.<br/><br/>
In the first graph above, `cluster_0` is calculated first. At this time, it is found that the total length of the rank from `a0` to `a3` is not enough to fully contain the content of the label, and the left and right margins of `cluster_0` and `rank[2,3]` and `rank[6, 7]` the distance between.<br/><br/>
Then start to calculate the label length of `cluster_4` at this time, and find that the two ranks before and after `d` are not long enough, and choose to stretch the distance between the left and right margins of `cluster_4` and `rank[3,4]` and `rank[4,5]`. <br/><br/>
After the completion of `cluster_4`, the distance between the first rank of `cluster_0` and the last rank is enough to accommodate the label of `cluster_0`, resulting in the above result.

