I've been thinking about refactoring the structure of agxbuf and thought I'd write up some of my thoughts for people to consider.

## Background

`agxbuf` is a Graphviz type for dynamic string construction. You can think of it as the equivalent of C++'s `std::ostringstream`, or even more closely POSIX's `open_memstream`. It can be in two different states, external storage or heap-allocated:

```c
// setting up a buffer with external storage
char backing[10]; // ← backing memory for the buffer
agxbuf external_buf1 = {0};
agxbinit(&buf1, sizeof(backing), backing);

// setting up a buffer with heap-allocation
agxbuf buf2 = {0};
```

When a buffer with external storage is about to overflow, it will switch to heap-allocated. So the caller does not need to think about the bounds of the buffer.

Something I have been thinking about is supporting a third state, inline storage. For small amounts of data, the members of the struct can be repurposed to store the data _itself_. This is a technique known as Small/Short String Optimization¹ (SSO). The advantage of this is that smaller strings (likely the default in Graphviz) need no allocation at all.

A secondary thing I've been thinking about is packing an `agxbuf` itself into fewer bytes. This actually _decreases_ the number of strings eligible for SSO (the available inline space shrinks), but `agxbuf` objects are created frequently, so maybe it's worth shrinking their stack footprint.

So how do we achieve these things? Lets look at some possible changes below. Note that almost all involve moving from a (base pointer, end pointer) pair to a (base pointer, extent) pair because the latter is a bit easier to think about.

## Option 0 – leave as-is

As a point of comparison, the current layout of `agxbuf` is:

```c
/* Extensible buffer:
 *  Malloc'ed memory is never released until agxbfree is called.
 */
typedef struct {
  char *buf;           // start of buffer
  char *ptr;           // next place to write
  char *eptr;          // end of buffer
  int stack_allocated; // false if buffer is malloc'ed
} agxbuf;
```

It's possible the optimizations above and below are not worth it (we should profile some expensive cases). So leaving the struct as-is is a real option.

## Packing the stack/heap bit

```c
typedef struct {
  char *buf;                               // start of buffer
  size_t size;                             // number of bytes used
  size_t capacity: sizeof(size_t) * 8 - 1; // number of bytes available
  bool stack_allocated: 1;                 // false if buffer is malloc'ed
} agxbuf;
```

This shrinks the structure by `sizeof(int)` (4 bytes on x86 and x86-64). We can no longer manage a string with backing memory ≥ 2⁶³ on x86-64 (2³¹ on x86), but it seems unlikely we need such a thing anyway. Note that the upper bit of `.size` is useless because we now cannot increase the backing memory to support a string of this size.

## Introducing SSO

```c
typedef struct {
  char *buf;                               // start of buffer
  size_t size;                             // number of bytes used
  size_t capacity: sizeof(size_t) * 8 - 2; // number of bytes available
  unsigned location: 2;                    // out-of-line, inline, or heap
} agxbuf;
```

We need to enlarge the field used for indicating the location of the backing memory. We now need 2 bits, because we have 3 possibilities. Lets choose the encoding `0b00` = inline, `0b01` = out-of-line, `0b10` = heap. This may seem like an arbitrary choice, but it is not. Using `0b00` for inline allows us to have a naturally NUL terminated buffer. To explain, lets look at a more complete definition:

```c
typedef struct {
  union {
    char raw[sizeof(char*) + sizeof(size_t) + sizeof(size_t)];
    struct {
      char *buf;                               // start of buffer
      size_t size;                             // number of bytes used
      size_t capacity: sizeof(size_t) * 8 - 2; // number of bytes available
      unsigned location: 2;                    // out-of-line, inline, or heap
    };
  };
} agxbuf;
```

The `.raw` member is what we use for the backing memory when the string is inline. But we can't use the last byte because some of its bits are the very data we examine to determine _if_ this string is inline. By choosing `0b00` to mean inline, we can leave the last byte NUL so we have a well-formed string. Note that having a NUL terminator is _required_ when we're storing the string inline, because we no longer have a `.size` member. We need to rely on `strlen` to tell us the size of the string.

## More intelligent packing

We noted that the initial packing lost us a bit from both `.size` and `.capacity`. The SSO expansion of this field to 2 bits lost us a further bit. Can we reclaim this somehow?

```c
typedef struct {
  union {
    char raw[sizeof(char*) + sizeof(size_t) + sizeof(size_t)];
    struct {
      char *buf;                               // start of buffer
      size_t size: sizeof(size_t) * 8 - 1;     // number of bytes used
      bool is_stack: 1;
      size_t capacity: sizeof(size_t) * 8 - 1; // number of bytes available
      bool is_not_inline: 1;
    };
  };
} agxbuf;
```

By splitting `.location` across two discontiguous bits, we regain 63 bits (resp 31 bits) of both `.size` and `.capacity`. The cost here is a more complex location determination. It is not valid to look at the `.is_stack` bit until you have examined the `.is_not_inline` bit. If the `.is_not_inline` bit is not set, the `.is_stack` bit is part of the string itself, not part of the location determination. Once again, the polarity of the inline bit (that we choose `0b0` to mean inline rather than `0b1`) is chosen to give us a natural NUL terminator.

## More advanced packing

```c
typedef struct {
  union {
    char raw[sizeof(char*) + sizeof(size_t)];
    struct {
      char *buf;        // start of buffer
      size_t metadata;  // size, capacity, location
    };
  };
} agxbuf;
```

Here we've lost all structure, so I'll have to explain in words the encoding I have in mind. The top two bits of `.metadata` determine the location. `0b00` mean inline (we retain our natural NUL terminator property), `0b01` mean stack, `0b1x` mean heap. It seems strange that I've put an `x` ("don't care") there and made both `0b10` and `0b11` mean heap, but we'll get to an explanation.

Once you chop off the top 2 bits of `.metadata`, the next set bit determines the capacity shifted left by 1. So e.g. if, after the top 2 bits, the next  set is way down in bit 16, the capacity of the buffer is 2¹⁵ bytes. The size of the buffer is the remaining bits below this. If you think about this for a while, you'll note this is taking advantage of the invariant that capacity ≥ size.

Checking for when we're about to exhaust the buffer has become a bit more complicated. And the buffer capacity can now only ever be a power of 2. So why are we using this bizarre encoding scheme? Well it drops the overall size of the structure by `sizeof(size_t)`. On x86-64 Linux, the struct will now fit in the in-register calling convention (though it's unclear how often we actually pass one of these by value).

I promised you an explanation of the cryptic `0b1x` encoding for heap. Well the scheme I've just described sacrifices 2 bits: we're back down to a maximum capacity of 2⁶⁰ (2²⁸ resp). We only expect buffers this large, if ever, on the heap. So by making the low bit of the heap encoding "don't care" we gain an extra bit, back up to 2⁶¹ (2²⁹ resp).

## Closing thoughts

The final iteration of this design above is so complex, we probably want to avoid it. But I wanted to lay it out anyway, as a thought exercise in how far we can push this.

We probably shouldn't do any of these before some profiling. But nevertheless I thought I should outline (no pun intended) my thoughts rather than let them continue to roll around uncritiqued in my head.

¹ I thought there was a wikipedia page for this, but it seems not. You can find various descriptions of this by searching the web.

